{"actual_usd":0.1269,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":304,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"\"I don't think that's as silly a question as people sometimes make it sound.\" *I rub a thumb through a dusting of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady into the room.* \"If Jesus is truly God and truly man, then in Gethsemane you're not watching a little stage trick. You're watching the Son speaking to the Father — real relationship, not God doing a bit with Himself.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the boards give a soft creak under my shift of weight.* \"Christians would say God is one, yes, but not solitary in the flat way people mean. Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. So no, not 'praying to himself' like a man muttering into a mirror. More like the Son, having taken on full human life, praying exactly as a faithful man ought to pray — and doing it in perfect communion with the Father.\"\n\n\"The hard, beautiful part is that Gethsemane only means anything if his anguish was real.\" *I lower my voice a touch.* \"Not pretend fear. Not rehearsed sorrow. 'Not my will, but yours' has weight because he's there in the flesh, obeying under pressure. I think that's true, more or less.\"\n\n*I rest my hand on the warm wood of the counter.* \"Was it the Trinity part that was snagging you, or the 'two wills' part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":36.852870000000024,"run_id":"c062dd74-fc77-4a51-a023-81e2eb9efe4f"}
